rate ownership of tenant plots never distributed in the 1949 Land Reform.From public sites of protest to backstage meetings and negotiations, from farming villages to university campuses, Abelmann's highly original study explores this movement as a complex process always in the making. Her discussion moves fluently between past and present, local and national, elites and dominated, and urban and rural. Touching on major historical issues, this ethnography of dissent explores contemporary popular nationalism and historical consciousness.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aLand tenurexKorea (South). 0aLand tenurezKorea (South). 0aSocial movementsxCase studiesxKorea (South). 0aSocial movementsxKorea (South). 0aSocial movementszKorea (South)vCase studies. 0aSocial movements. 0aTenant farmersxPolitical activityxKorea (South). 0aTenant farmersxPolitical activityzKorea (South). 4aAnthropology. 4aCultural & Social. 4aSocial Science. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh1 aAbelmann, Nancy, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000z97831106353480 cprintz978052020418840uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052091748440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520917484423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520917484/original  a978-3-11-063534-8  University of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles